The phylogenetic tree constructed by the gltA gene (Fig. 1
) showed that the bat isolates were grouped into an independent clade, separated from all Bartonella type/reference strains. The rodent and shrew isolates belonged to the same clade of B. tribocorum, B. elizabethae, B. grahamii, B. rattimassiliensis and B. queenslandensis (Fig. 1). In this specific clade, one isolate from Crocidura attenuata tanakae and one isolate from Rattus coxinga niviventer were formed a specific group with B. queenslandensis (bootstrap value >90%). Using the merged set of concatenated sequences of five genes (16S ribosomal DNA, ftsZ, gltA, ribC, and rpoB) to construct the phylogenetic relationship, the results also shown that the isolates from bats formed a significantly distinct clade comparing to the other Bartonella type/reference strains (Fig. 2
).
